If you compile this using Microsoft Visual C++ 2005 SP1: classFoo{
...
virtualvoidBar(constinti)=0;
};

classMockFoo:publicFoo{
...
MOCK_METHOD1(Bar,void(constinti));
};
 You may get the following warning: warningC4301:'MockFoo::Bar':overridingvirtualfunctiononlydiffersfrom'Foo::Bar'byconst/volatilequalifier

In C++, if you declare a function with a const parameter, the const modifier is ignored. Therefore, the Foo base class above is equivalent to: classFoo{
...
virtualvoidBar(inti)=0;//intorconstint?Makesnodifference.
};
